## Submission Guidelines

### What to submit

Every team must submit the following by the hackathon deadline:

- **`README.md`** — Project overview, problem statement, and agent architecture diagram
- **Source code** — Clean, runnable code in a public or shared GitHub repository
- **Demo video** — A 3–5 minute screen recording of your system running end-to-end (no cuts, no mocked outputs)
- **Architecture diagram** — A visual showing each agent, its role, and how agents communicate
- **Slide deck** — Maximum 10 slides 

### README template

Your project README must include:

```markdown
## [Project Name]

**Team:** [Names]
**Theme & Challenge:** [e.g. Theme 2 — Adaptive Curriculum Engine]
**Track:** [Hard / Medium / Open / Open Innovation]

### Problem statement
[1–2 sentences. What problem does your system solve?]

### Why multi-agent?
[Why does this problem require multiple cooperating agents?]

### Agent architecture
| Agent | Role |
|-------|------|
| Agent 1 | ... |
| Agent 2 | ... |

### How to run
[Step-by-step instructions to run your system locally]

### Demo
[Link to demo video]

### Tech stack
[Languages, frameworks, models, APIs used]
```

### Rules

- All code must be written during the hackathon — no pre-built solutions
- Use of open-source libraries, APIs, and pre-trained models is permitted and encouraged
- Submissions must be your own original work
- Mocked outputs or hardcoded demo paths will result in disqualification from the Technical Execution criterion

